<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-229  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 229.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Sept 3 1990 v7 n10 p30(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Connecting your LANs. (local area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Corrigan, Patrick H.; Guy, Aisling.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area networks (LANs) can communicate with other computersand other LANs.andP;  The types of communication approaches are: LAN toLAN repeaters, bridges, routers, and gateways to connect LANstogether locally; remote LAN to LAN bridges and routers; wide areanetwork gateways; mainframe or minicomputer host local or remotegateways; and asynchronous communications servers.andP;  One of themost common things a LAN user needs to do is dial in to the LANfrom a remote personal computer.andP;  This can be accomplished by aserial port on a file server; dialing in using an asynchronouscommunications server (ACS); dial in to the LAN through an ASC anduse the resources of an unused LAN personal computer; giving theremote user a LAN personal computer with a directly attachedmodem; or using a single personal computer and LAN connection tosupport multiple dial-in users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksMicrocomputersHardwareCommunicationConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Routers, bridges, repeaters connect at different layers of the OSIModel. (chart)Transparent-routing bridge. (chart)LAN router. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>